218: The Shape of Water, Phantom Thread, Her, Call Me by Your Name, There Will Be Blood, and Manchester by the Sea are movies that might be 10/10 for me on rewatch. I probably like some of these more than some of the lower favorite 10/10 rated movies I have

219: 24th favorite 10/10 film: Dunkirk (2017)
Dunkirk is a really good action movie that succeeds in everything it's going for as a thrill ride. The musical score combined with the situations the characters are put in works really well to create tension within the movie. Although I would say that this movie doesn't have many "flaws" there isn't that much that makes it stand out compared to my other 10/10s

220: 23d favorite 10/10 film: Memento (2000)
Memento is another Christopher Nolan film but is very different compared to Dunkirk. I'd classify it as a crime mystery thriller, where the main character loses his memory every 15 minutes. The best part of the movie is the way the story is structured, where every ~15 minutes it goes back in time to show what happened previously. Because of this structure we pretty much learn information as the main character learns it, and we're constantly questioning things related to the story like who the main character can trust and what events occurred before what's presented on screen. It's super interesting to watch from start to finish with an amazing plot/story, but like Dunkirk there aren't that many other things that stand out about it.

222: 22nd favorite 10/10 film: Nightcrawler (2014)
Nightcrawler is a drama thriller character study about the main characters dark economic climb when he is introduced to the business of filming crime scenes and accidents to sell to news stations. It's super entertaining from start to finish because of how well the main character and plot is written in addition to Jake Gyllenhaals amazing performance. I would say that it's one of most crowd-pleasing out of the 10/10s I have and it's on netflix so if youre bored and looking for something to watch I would highly recommend

223: 21st favorite 10/10 film: The Sixth Sense (1999)
Its been a really long time since Ive seen the sixth sense so it might not be as good as I remember it being but I remember loving it a lot when I saw it. It pretty much covers all of my favorite aspects in movies, being a heart touching drama with great characters and an amazing unique story. It's considered as a classic and I'd recommend watching it without knowing anything about the plot, but if you want to know more about it just be careful because this movie can easily be spoiled

224: 20th favorite 10/10 film: Inglourious Basterds(2009)
A great Tarantino film that's entertaining from start to finish. The best aspects of this movie is the comedy, the many quick small setups and payoffs sprinkled throughout the movie, the overall plot, and especially the main antagonist whos perfectly written and acted, and is arguably the main character as well. Small flaws is that its not super memorable and although I really like it, its just not the type of movie that I would consider to be among my absolute favorites

225: 19th favorite 10/10 film: The Royal Tenenbaums(2001)
First Wes Anderson movie on this list!! The Royal Tenenbaums is a charming comedy drama film about a family that has been separated for many years, until an event occurs that brings them together. From this movie it's super cool to see an early stage of Wes Anderson's unique style. You can tell that the camerawork/framing isn't at the level of perfection and precision he reaches in The Grand Budapest Hotel or Isle of Dogs, but that kind of precision isn't really necessary for a story like this, and I would even argue that it is better without it. The general plot of a family coming together might seem very boring/generic, but Wes Anderson's unique/quirky characters and comedy is what makes this film so great. It's also free on amazon prime :YEP:
also this is where a lot of the spots of these movies are a bit interchangeable

226: 18th favorite 10/10 film: Requiem for a Dream (2000)
If you watch this movie it'll make you never want to do drugs. The movie is about characters who deal with addiction and/or tragedy in different ways, and the content shown on screen gets really fucked up, disgusting, and terrifying. The musical score also adds to the fucked-upness, and the editing especially does as well. Just be careful if youre easily grossed out i guess lol
also if you want to add to the experience you can watch it at 1 am like I did

227: 17th favorite 10/10 film: Moonlight (2016)
This movie is about a gay black boy growing up and covers 3 main sections of his life, and it's one of the most intimate movies ive ever seen. The biggest highlight of the movie is the performances. There's a different actor that plays the main character and another character in each of the 3 sections, and theyre all great. The performances for the mother and mahershala alis character are even better though and they both have some really powerful scenes. The musical score is pretty good but the "The Middle of the World" piece is legitimately transcendent. Something thats funny is that I first watched it around when it came out and I'm pretty sure I barely understood anything about the themes of the movie and what kind of story it was trying to tell and I was just left feeling meh after it but after rewatching it 2 more times this year I definitely consider it to be amazing
fun fact the guy in the poster is composed of 3 diff ppl

228: 16th favorite 10/10 film: Isle of Dogs (2018)
Isle of dogs is a stop motion animated film that takes place in the near future in Japan where all dogs have been banished onto an island, and a boy goes out to look for his dog. What's great about this movie is that it's just a flawless execution of Wes Anderson's typical style: Great camerawork and framing, hilarious script, line delivery, and use of movie tropes, great plot and world building, and a another great unique and zany musical score by Alexandre Desplat. Overall just a great fun story about a boy and his dog with some deeper themes and metaphors if you want to see it that way or analyze it more

229: In filmmaking there is something called the 180 rule, which is a basic guideline to have the camera not cross an imaginary line passing through two characters in a scene. This is so that when you switch to different angles one character is always to the right of the frame. If the rule is broken it kind of looks like the character is teleporting to different sides in the scene.
Im bringing this up because while I was rewatching Arrival with joe i noticed in the dream sequence that they intentionally broke the rule as a way to disorient the audience
its in the scene that starts at 1:00 and the cut that breaks the rule is at 1:06
